Project: Investigate a Dataset - No-show appointments¶

Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row. This dataset is originally taken from Kaggle.

Dataset Columns¶

PatientId¶

  • Identification of a patient.

AppointmentID¶

  • Identification of each appointment.

Gender¶

  • Male or Female.

ScheduledDay¶

  • The day the patient set up their appointment.

AppointmentDay¶

  • The actual day of the appointment.

Age¶

  • How old the patient is.

Neighbourhood¶

  • The location of the hospital.

Scholarship¶

  • True of False. Whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família.

Hipertension¶

  • True or False

Diabetes¶

  • True or False

Alcoholism¶

  • True or False

Handcap¶

  • True or False

SMS_received¶

  • 1 or more messages sent to the patient.

No-show¶

  • 'Yes' or 'No'. 'Yes' means the patient did not come, while 'No' means that the patient visited the doctor on the appointment day.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

The factors that are important for us to know in which cases patients will not visit the scheduled appointment:

  1. Which age and gender groups had the most number of 'No-show' cases?
  2. Which locations had the most number of 'No-show' cases?
  3. People suffering from which illness had the most number of 'No-show' cases?
  4. Do the appointment days have an impact on the number of 'No-show' cases?

There seems to be issues with the values of the Age and Handcap columns. The minimum age cannot be -1. Handcap column was also said to contain either true or false values. We will address these issues in the data cleaning section.

Data Cleaning¶

Modify the data types¶

We have seen the problems with the data types of the ScheduledDay and AppointmentDay columns. We change them to datetime from string.

In [7]:
# convert the data types to datetime
df['ScheduledDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df['ScheduledDay'])
df['AppointmentDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df['AppointmentDay'])

It looks like the values are given according to the level of handicap severeness as there are a lot of rows with the values larger than 1. Since we are only interested whether the patient has disabilities or not, we can replace the values larger than 1 with 1, which indicates true.

In [14]:
# apply lambda function to replace the values
df['Handcap'] = df['Handcap'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x >= 1 else 0)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

1. Which age and gender groups had the most number of 'No-show' cases?¶

Let us first see the percentages of patients who visited the hospital or not using the pie chart.

In [19]:
# Create a figure and axis
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 6))

# Prepare the data for pie chart
no_show_series = df['No_show'].value_counts()

# Define colors for the pie chart slices
colors = ['#66b3ff', '#ff6666']  # Light blue for "Visited", Light red for "Not visited"

# Plot the pie chart with customized options
ax.pie(no_show_series.values, labels=['Visited', 'Not visited'], autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, colors=colors,
       wedgeprops={'edgecolor': 'black', 'linewidth': 1.5, 'linestyle': 'solid'})

# Add a title with custom font style and size
plt.title("The Number of Medical Appointment Cases")

# Show the plot
plt.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle.
plt.show()

Bar chart to see the distribution of 'No-show' cases¶

In [21]:
# Create a figure and axis
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
no_show_gender = df_no_show['Gender'].value_counts()

plt.bar(['Female', 'Male'], no_show_gender.values);
In [23]:
# Calculate the Show-up cases by subtracting No-show cases from Total appointments
total_gender = df['Gender'].value_counts()
no_show_gender = df_no_show['Gender'].value_counts()
show_up_gender = total_gender - no_show_gender

# Calculate the percentage of No-show and Show-up cases
no_show_percentage_gender = (no_show_gender / total_gender) * 100
show_up_percentage_gender = (show_up_gender / total_gender) * 100

# Create the stacked bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.title("Hospital Appointments by Gender")
plt.xlabel("Gender")
plt.ylabel("Number of Cases")

# Stacked bar plot: No-show cases in red, Show-up cases in lightgreen
bars1 = plt.bar(['Female', 'Male'], no_show_gender, label='No-show', color='lightcoral', edgecolor='black')
bars2 = plt.bar(['Female', 'Male'], show_up_gender, bottom=no_show_gender, label='Show-up', color='lightgreen', edgecolor='black')

# Add percentage labels inside the bars
for i, (no_show, show_up, no_show_pct, show_up_pct) in enumerate(zip(no_show_gender, show_up_gender, no_show_percentage_gender, show_up_percentage_gender)):
    # No-show percentage label
    plt.text(i, no_show / 2, f'{no_show_pct:.1f}%', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black')
    # Show-up percentage label
    plt.text(i, no_show + show_up / 2, f'{show_up_pct:.1f}%', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black')

# Add legend
plt.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Calculate the Show-up cases by subtracting No-show cases from Total appointments
show_up_cases = df_weekdays.values - noshow_weekdays.values

# Calculate the percentage of No-show and Show-up cases
no_show_percentage = (noshow_weekdays.values / df_weekdays.values) * 100
show_up_percentage = (show_up_cases / df_weekdays.values) * 100

# Create the stacked bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.title('No-show vs Show-up Appointments on Weekdays')
plt.xlabel('Days of the week')
plt.ylabel('Number of cases')

bars2 = plt.bar(noshow_weekdays.index, show_up_cases, bottom=noshow_weekdays.values, label='Show-up', color='lightgreen', edgecolor='black')

# Add percentage labels inside the bars
for i, (no_show, show_up, no_show_pct, show_up_pct) in enumerate(zip(noshow_weekdays.values, show_up_cases, no_show_percentage, show_up_percentage)):
    # Skip Saturday (index 5) from labeling
    if df_weekdays.index[i] == 5:  # Saturday's index is 5
        continue
    # No-show percentage label
    plt.text(i, no_show / 2, f'{no_show_pct:.1f}%', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black')
    # Show-up percentage label
    plt.text(i, no_show + show_up_cases[i] / 2, f'{show_up_pct:.1f}%', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black')

Conclusions¶

The factors that are important for us to know in which cases patients will not visit the scheduled appointment:

1. Which age and gender groups had the most number of 'No-show' cases?¶

The largest number of male patients who did not come to the appointment were members of the 0-20 age group. Meanwhile, the group interval was about 20-40 for the female ones. Almost the same percentages of people from both groups missed their appointments (about 20%).

2. Which locations had the most number of 'No-show' cases?¶

The hospitals of JARDIM CAMBURI and MARIA ORTIZ had the most number of no-show patients during the given period with 1465 and 1219 cases, respectively. However, the RESISTENCIA hospital was the first in terms of percentages (about 26% of the patients did not show up).

3. People suffering from which illness had the most number of 'No-show' cases?¶

The people who suffer from hypertension did not come to the appointments most of the times compared to other provided illnesses with the noticeably large difference. It was due to the fact that many people had scheduled appointments for this illness. Thus, alcoholism was number one in terms of percentages (about 20%).

4. Do the appointment days have an impact on the number of 'No-show' cases?¶

Almost all the days had similar proportions of “no-show” cases (about 20%). Nevertheless, Thursday was the day with the fewest cases. It is worth noting almost no hospitals scheduled the appointment for Saturdays. The median number of total “no-show” cases was about 5000 over the weekdays.

Limitations¶

Due to the lack of scheduled appointment hours in the dataset, it was not possible to analyse the specific parts of the days when the patients would not come.

Moreover, the location, illness and week_day based values of no-show cases were large due to the overall value counts of the dataset.

Project: A Simple Classification Model¶

Data Preprocessing¶

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer

# Check for missing values
df.isnull().sum()

# Impute missing values for numerical columns (e.g., Age)
imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
df['Age'] = imputer.fit_transform(df[['Age']])

# Encode categorical columns (Gender, Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap, SMS_received)
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
df['Gender'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Gender'])
df['Scholarship'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Scholarship'])
df['Hipertension'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Hipertension'])
df['Diabetes'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Diabetes'])
df['Alcoholism'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Alcoholism'])
df['Handcap'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Handcap'])
df['SMS_received'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['SMS_received'])
df['No_show'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['No_show'])

# Convert 'ScheduledDay' and 'AppointmentDay' to datetime format
df['ScheduledDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df['ScheduledDay'])
df['AppointmentDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df['AppointmentDay'])

# Feature Engineering: Extract features from the date columns
df['ScheduledWeekday'] = df['ScheduledDay'].dt.weekday
df['ScheduledHour'] = df['ScheduledDay'].dt.hour
df['ScheduledMonth'] = df['ScheduledDay'].dt.month
df['AppointmentWeekday'] = df['AppointmentDay'].dt.weekday
df['AppointmentHour'] = df['AppointmentDay'].dt.hour

# Drop the original 'ScheduledDay' and 'AppointmentDay' columns as we extracted useful features
df = df.drop(columns=['ScheduledDay', 'AppointmentDay'])

Feature Selection¶

We will use the following columns as features:

  • Age
  • Gender
  • Scholarship
  • Hipertension
  • Diabetes
  • Alcoholism
  • Handcap
  • SMS_received
  • ScheduledWeekday
  • ScheduledHour
  • ScheduledMonth
  • AppointmentWeekday
  • AppointmentHour

The target variable is No-show (1 for no-show, 0 for show-up).
